<TEXT>
three zeros mean nothing by themselves but 
leaving them off the end of a number is going to cost the nations 
largest insurer at least 8 million 
prudential insurance co of america is offering the payment to 
settle claims resulting from a clerical error in which a lien it 
held was listed as worth 92885 instead of 92885000 
us bankruptcy judge howard buschman iii heard closing 
arguments on the proposed settlement tuesday and is expected to 
rule in several days 
why because of a clerical error should we give up 92 
millionplus prudential spokesman joseph vecchione said tuesday 
if buschman knocks down the proposed settlement and decides the 
lien is only worth 92885 prudential would collect only that 
much the rest of its claim would be thrown into the pool with 
other creditors 
the case is part of the chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings of 
mclean industries inc parent of united states lines prudential 
holds the lien in connection with mortgages on eight of the 
companys container ships 
the sale of the eight lancerclass ships was expected to raise 
at least 51 million all of which ordinarily would go to 
prudential because the lien puts it at the head of the line of 
creditors 
but the missing zeros have weakened prudentials standing 
prudential is proposing to pay the shipping company 17 percent 
of the sales net proceeds an estimated 8 million that money 
would be distributed among other creditors most of whom support 
the proposal 
but general electric capital corp which shares a second 
mortgage on the ships with prudential opposes the deal saying the 
lien should be considered worth 92885 
the settlement is not in the best interests of the bankruptcy 
estate sandy mayerson a lawyer representing ge capital said 
tuesday 
prudential says the clerical error repeated on at least 20 
documents was committed by someone at a law firm it once used 
haight gardner poor and havens 
prudential has said it has not decided whether to file 
malpractice lawsuits against haight gardner and its overall 
outside counsel on the transaction dewey ballantine bushby palmer 
amp wood both law firms have declined to comment 
</TEXT>
