<DOCNO> AP880323-0012 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the most detailed survey of the milky way 
will start thursday at the worlds most sensitive radio telescope 
an array of 27 dishshaped antennas spread across new mexicos 
desert 
without a doubt this will give us the most comprehensive 
picture of our galaxy yet obtained in any kind of wavelength 
including visible light and radio and infrared radiation said 
robert h becker associate professor of astronomy at the 
university of california davis 
the 1 million twoyear survey will be conducted by becker and 
astronomer david helfand of columbia university they will use the 
very large array radio telescope a set of 27 antenna dishes each 
about 80 feet in diameter that move on 20 miles of tracks west of 
socorro nm 
the telescope which started operations in the late 1970s can 
detect fainter radio signals than any other radio telescope becker 
said tuesday during a telephone interview 
more complete surveys of the heavens beyond our galaxy have been 
conducted using powerful optical and infrared telescopes aimed to 
look above or below the milky ways flattened disk 
but such telescopes cant survey our own galaxy very well 
because visible light is blocked by tremendous amounts of dust 
between the milky ways stars and because the galaxy is so full of 
infrared light sources that its hard to distinguish various 
objects becker said 
the survey will construct maps of the 70 percent of the milky 
way visible from the northern hemisphere by detecting objects that 
emit radio waves which penetrate the dust 
such objects include supernovas or dying exploding stars vast 
dustandgas clouds where new stars are born and very dense 
supernova remnants called neutron stars pulsars and black holes 
what this kind of survey can do is give you the overall 
picture becker said until you catalog the contents of your 
own galaxy youre never going to have a clear picture of what the 
galaxy is 
the diskshaped milky way contains an estimated 100 billion 
stars clumped in spiraling arms that stretch across 100000 light 
years or about 588000 trillion miles of space earth is located 
roughly 22000 light years or 130000 trillion miles from the 
galaxys center 
becker said the survey undoubtedly will produce unexpected 
discoveries but also could help astronomers determine the 
frequency and location of supernova explosions invisible to optical 
telescopes 
shock waves from such explosions are thought to compress gas and 
dust to create new stars 
the survey will help determine if that theory is correct by 
showing if there is a link between the location of supernovas and 
regions of star formation becker said 
while some stars leave nothing behind after they explode as 
supernovas other supernovas collapse into dense neutron stars 
rotating neutron stars called pulsars or even more dense objects 
called black holes which have gravity so intense that not even 
light escapes 
becker said the survey should help astronomers learn what 
proportion of supernovas become neutron stars pulsars or black 
holes because such objects generate radio signals 
while the survey wont detect life that might exist elsewhere in 
the galaxy it could help scientists improve estimates of the odds 
that such life exists becker said 
if one wants to estimate the probability of finding 
intelligent life elsewhere in our galaxy you have to know what the 
environment of our galaxy is including the number of objects 
that may be orbited by inhabited planets he said 
recent improvements to the very large array gave it a much 
larger field of view so it will take fewer pointings of the 
telescope to map out the milky way becker said 
becker and helfand will have 300 hours of viewing time during 
the survey they then will spend another year or two using 
computers to contruct maps using the detected radio signals 
the first 20 to 24 hours of surveyrelated observations will 
start thursday and end saturday with more intermittent 
observations regularly scheduled during the next two years each 
time the antennas are reaimed becker said 
the survey is financed by the university of california the 
national science foundation and lawrence livermore national 
laboratory 
 
</TEXT>
