<TEXT>
senior police officers say the dramatic 
increase in weapons seizures at the capitol last year involved not 
lethal guns or knives but small canisters of chemical sprays that 
women visitors carry in their handbags for selfprotection 
house sergeant at arms jack russ created a stir recently when he 
reported that capitol police confiscated 1162 weapons in 1987 a 
startling 147 percent increase over seizures in the previous year 
but capitol police chief frank kerrigan said in an interview 
that the 1162 cited by russ were all canisters of mace or other 
brands of nonlethal chemical sprays some in lipstickstyle 
containers that are used to immobilize wouldbe attackers 
chemical sprays are illegal throughout the district of columbia 
including the capitol where police classify them as weapons 
subject to seizure and destruction 
in fact kerrigan said 1270 weapons were seized last year and 
selfdefense sprays accounted for the vast majority of them 
seizures of guns actually declined by 50 percent last year 
kerrigan said 
russ said he must have misinterpreted data he obtained from the 
capitol police when he reported that the 1162 spray seizures 
represented all weapons confiscated last year 
russ cited that figure at a house appropriations subcommittee 
hearing to justify his request for 185 million to tighten 
security on the house side of the capitol arguing that police face 
a growing threat of violent attacks 
rep vic fazio dcalif chairman of the house panel said russ 
left the impression that most of the weapons seizures last year 
involved guns which probably was a misimpression on the part 
of the sergeant at arms 
but fazio said his subcommittee intends to take a much closer 
look at the issue in consultation with the senate before making 
any decisions we wont be stampeded he said 
rep jerry lewis of california ranking republican on the house 
subcommittee said he didnt know whether russ had manipulated the 
weapons figures to attract support for his security plan but said 
any such proposals should be studied with caution 
theyre pushing very hard to increase security everywhere up 
here lewis said we must protect ourselves in this modern age 
of terrorism but i tend to resist any unnecessary steps that would 
hinder the publics access to the capitol 
of the 1987 total kerrigan said the 1162 chemical spray 
seizures represent a sharp increase over the previous year when 
470 such sprays were confiscated 
the rest of last years total included guns knives and other 
potentially deadly weapons including clubs blackjacks and brass 
knuckles and nonlethal stun guns which knock out their victims 
with electrical shocks authorities said 
stun guns aside the total of deadly weapons seized last year 
increased by only three over those confiscated in 1986 kerrigan 
said last years total included only 14 guns exactly half the 28 
that were seized in 1986 the police said 
kerrigan said the escalating weapons seizures probably reflect 
improved use of metal detectors in the capitol building and six 
nearby office buildings better training of police officers and 
more thorough searches of visitors 
considering the sharp increase in discovery of the chemical 
spray canisters kerrigan said it could be that people are more 
aware of the need to protect themselves 
kerrigan said 63 people were prosecuted at the capitol last year 
on illegal weapons charges compared with 50 people in 1986 
generally visitors carrying deadly weapons are arrested but those 
with chemical sprays are not he said 
asked by sen harry reid dnev how many visitors enter the 
capitol with evil intent senate sergeant at arms harry henry 
giugni said he didnt know but he recalled that an 85yearold 
woman from tennessee was found carrying a handgun that would have 
blown up in her hand if shed tried to fire it 
giugni said the woman told capitol police that her hometown 
sheriff had advised her to take a gun if she planned to visit 
washington 
</TEXT>
