<DOCNO> AP880323-0020 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
advocates of continued trade protection for 
the american steel industry are citing a new congressional study 
concluding that quotas cant be blamed for last years steel price 
increases 
the congressional research service said in a 23page report 
tuesday that last years steel price hike of about 47 percent 
probably had more to do with changes in the exchange rate than with 
the reagan administrations import restraints 
the report comes in the last full year of the administrations 
program of signing agreements with japan south korea and other 
major steelexporting nations to curb the flow of subsidized 
foreign steel into the united states 
the fiveyear program ends in september 1989 and big steel 
companies are already pushing for commitments from congress and 
presidential contenders on whether the import barriers will be 
extended 
imports account for about 21 percent of the american steel 
market down from nearly 26 percent when the quotas began in late 
1984 
opposing continuing the quotas are american companies that rely 
on imported steel and which claim that the reagan program has 
stifled competition raised prices and caused harmful shortages 
erwin l klein president of the american institute for imported 
steel said in december that it would be improper for more 
government intervention to determine the future of the american 
steel market and the united states economy instead we believe 
free enterprise must prevail 
the institute represents 70 steel importers in the united states 
the congressional report however said changes in exchange 
rates have helped raise the price of steel imports by about 45 
percent nearly identical to the price rise in the domestic 
industry that suggests that there is considerable competition in 
the us market the report said 
the report said many countries covered by the reagan plan appear 
not to have filled their quotas last year the argument can be 
made that domestic steel buyers were able to obtain as much 
imported steel as they wanted before being confronted by the import 
barriers it said 
the report was released by sen john heinz rpa who had 
pushed the white house for import relief before the program began 
in 1984 
heinz said the report ought to be the final americanmade nail 
in the coffin for these nagging complaints that the steel program 
has boosted domestic prices 
the congressional research service said nothing in this 
report should be taken as an argument in favor of or opposed to 
the import restraints of the presidents steel program it said 
the reports goal was merely to evaluate claims that the quotas 
caused prices to rise 
david e levy spokesman for the american institute for imported 
steel reiterated the groups position against extending the 
quotas but said he had not seen the report and could not comment 
on it 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

