<TEXT>
here are the major provisions of the civil 
rights restoration act as they apply to the four statutes 
protecting women minorities the elderly and the handicapped from 
federally subsidized discrimination 
compliance with the statutes is required of entire departments 
and agencies of state and local governments when any part of the 
department or agency receives federal aid 
compliance is required throughout entire colleges universities 
and public school systems if any program or activity receives 
federal aid 
compliance is required of entire corporations and private 
organizations if federal aid is extended to them as a whole or if 
they are principally involved in providing education health care 
housing social services or parks or recreation otherwise 
compliance is limited to the plant or facility receiving the aid 
ultimate beneficiaries of federal aid such as farmers 
receiving crop subsidies or people getting food stamps or social 
security do not come under federal civil rights regulation 
small providers such as mom and pop grocery stores are given 
flexibility in making their facilities accessible to handicapped 
people 
people with contagious diseases or infections are considered 
handicapped and protected by civil rights laws unless they pose a 
direct threat to the health or safety of others or are unable to 
perform their jobs 
institutions and individuals are not required to perform or pay 
for abortions or services relating to them no penalties are 
permitted against people seeking benefits or services related to an 
abortion 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

