<TEXT>
spending big money on space age hospital 
equipment is not necessarily the best way to provide quality 
medical care says the federal governments top health official 
sometimes our hightech capability lures us into pursuing 
expensive answers when less costly ones are available dr otis 
r bowen said tuesday our veneration of technology has become a 
cultural blind spot that sometimes keeps us from pursuing practical 
solutions to our problems 
the health and human service secretarys remarks to a conference 
of the health care quality alliance came shortly after the 
28member coalition issued a report saying cost control should stop 
where quality of care and quality of life are adversely 
affected 
bowen said cost containment and quality care can coexist 
sometimes you can save money and also improve care like 
concentrating certain procedures in hospitals that specialize in 
them he said this not only leads to better results for the 
patient it also allows us to benefit from economies of scale 
one reason todays health care is so expensive is that the 
financing of that care is little more than a collection of 
disincentives to practice costeffective medicine 
hospitals in order to attract doctors and their patients 
have bought and often duplicated the latest in medical hardware in 
a kind of medical arms race 
he said exempting employerpaid health insurance coverage from 
federal income taxes has encouraged employers and unions to 
bargain for evergreater firstdollar coverage in health insurance 
plans 
compounding this folly most insurance plans cover expensive 
hightech procedures and slight preventive services bowen added 
and all of this has made patients and their families all but 
oblivious to costs since they pay so little out of pocket 
bowen said the establishment of the federal medicare health 
program for the elderly in 1965 created a powerful incentive for 
the health care industry to develop the technology to treat the 
chronic degenerative diseases that afflict the aging 
while that has improved the quality of life for americans of 
all ages bowen said the nation has yet to face difficult 
questions of how best to allocate health dollars in the modern era 
still to be decided is how much is too much he said how 
much heroic medical care and how many procedures to keep a dying 
patient alive are desirable for the patient the family and not 
least of all for society at large when is such care merely 
prolonging the act of dying rather than contributing to longer 
life or at least some type of quality to it 
bowen is a 70yearold physician whose first wife died in 1981 
after a long battle with bone cancer and whose mother recently died 
in a nursing home 
the alliance membership includes the american medical 
association the alzheimers disease and related disorders 
association the arthritis foundation the american cancer society 
the american academy of pediatrics and the national council on the 
aging 
