<TEXT>
the department of defense has decided to begin 
aids testing on civilian workers destined for overseas assignments 
with an estimated 8000 men and women to be affected during the 
first year officials said tuesday 
no date for the start of civilian screening has yet been 
established said the pentagon which already operates the worlds 
largest aids testing program 
the aids blood test will be administered to civilian workers 
during a complete physical examination which will become mandatory 
for those drawing overseas assignments 
the approach is similar to that now used by the state 
department the pentagon officials said 
in another move deputy defense secretary william h taft iv has 
authorized the army to draft a legislative proposal that would make 
it easier to discharge service members on a medical disability if 
they test positively for the aids virus 
such legislation if ever enacted could provide the military 
with a means of discharging servicemen as soon as they test 
positively for exposure regardless of whether theyre showing any 
symptoms yet of the deadly disease itself 
one way to do that the sources explained tuesday is to broaden 
the legal definition of a military disability 
currently no individual on active duty who tests positively for 
aids on a blood test can be discharged without showing other 
medical symptoms of the disease 
the decisions involving aids policies were first disclosed early 
this month by defense sources who requested anonymity the defense 
department subsequently confirmed the actions while insisting in a 
written statement to the associated press that taft had issued 
preliminary guidance without yet signing any final directives 
the decision has been made even if a directive hasnt been 
signed countered one source he was presented options and made 
up his mind 
aids acquired immune deficiency syndrome attacks the bodys 
immune system and its ability to resist infection no cure has been 
found for the disease which can be spread through sexual contact 
and tainted blood 
the pentagon citing the need to protect military blood 
supplies routinely tests all 21 million men and women on active 
duty as well as all recruit applicants a service member who tests 
positively but who is not disabled by the disease is restricted 
to duty inside the united states and may be limited in job 
assignments 
a recruit who tests positively is denied admission to the 
military 
despite the massive commitment to aids screening which began in 
october 1985 the pentagon has until recently focused only on 
military personnel 
according to sources the army has repeatedly urged aids testing 
for all defense department workers as well as automatic discharge 
or dismissal for those testing positively defense health officials 
have always rebuffed those suggestions saying they were too 
farreaching 
the sources said taft had finally decided to take the middle 
road when it came to civilians focusing only on those who draw 
assignments outside the united states 
the new program is expected to cost roughly 16 million a year 
one official said 
</TEXT>
