<TEXT>
ortho pharmaceutical corp says it will 
challenge a state appellate courts decision upholding a jurys 
verdict that the diaphragm manufacturer was responsible for a 
womans toxic shock syndrome 
in a 36page ruling tuesday the middlelevel court of appeals 
said there was sufficient evidence to justify a maricopa county 
superior court jurys 15 million verdict against ortho 
manufacturer of the ortho allflex diaphragm 
the verdict was the first to hold a pharmaceutical manufacturer 
responsible for a case of toxic shock syndrome according to the 
appellate court and the plaintiffs lawyer 
tss is an acute and sometimes fatal illness caused by a 
bacterium staphylococcus aureus that produces a poison the 
ailment is most closely associated with tampon use 
the case was brought in phoenix by roberta baroldy whose 
physician prescribed an ortho allflex diaphragm in april 1982 
about six weeks after the birth of her first child 
ortho pharmaceutical has since issued warnings on the 
possibility of toxic shock syndrome but court records show that 
the company had been warned by at least one doctor of a possible 
tss link nearly four months before mrs baroldys illness in july 
1982 and had not publicized the warning 
mrs baroldy was hospitalized for 41 days and was at times 
comatose and near death the 30 appellate ruling noted 
mrs baroldys medical witnesses testified that she would have 
physical problems for the rest of her life as a result of the 
disease 
we will appeal ortho spokesman rich salem said tuesday at 
corporate headquarters in raritan nj beyond that wed like a 
chance to actually see the opinion before we comment further 
the company a subsidiary of johnson amp johnson and has sold 
millions of the contraceptive devices over more than 40 years 
according to court records 
about 18 million diaphragms are sold each year in the united 
states salem said adding that he did not know orthos share of 
the market 
orthos attorneys argued on appeal that the theory under which 
experts claimed that mrs baroldy was stricken did not have the 
required general acceptance in the scientific community 
they also argued that the case should have been tried using 
north carolina laws because mrs baroldy was in north carolina at 
the time of her illness while her husband was taking parachute 
training at fort bragg 
but the appeals court said it was satisfied that testimony from 
a broad crosssection of experts showed general acceptance of a 
link between diaphragms and tss 
and the judges said arizonas product liability law was more 
appropriate than north carolina law because it was closer to the 
laws in new jersey where ortho is headquartered and because the 
baroldys who are from the globe ariz area were living in mesa 
at the time the suit was tried 
