<TEXT>
police on the lookout for terrorist attacks at 
the capitol report a 50 percent decline in seizures of handguns and 
rifles last year but a sharp increase in canisters of chemical 
sprays that visitors carry for selfprotection 
figures supplied by senior police officials appeared to 
contradict an earlier claim by house sergeantatarms jack russ 
that weapons seizures rose by a startling 147 percent at the 
capitol last year 
members of a house appropriations subcommittee said russ left 
the impression at a recent hearing that many of the 1162 
confiscated weapons were guns russ cited the figure in arguing for 
an 185 million plan to tighten security on the house side of the 
capitol 
but capitol police chief frank kerrigan said in a subsequent 
interview that all 1162 actually were canisters of mace tear gas 
and other nonlethal chemical sprays some in lipstickstyle 
containers that women carry to immobilize wouldbe attackers the 
same seizures totaled 470 the previous year 
tear gas and other chemical sprays are illegal in the district 
of columbia including the capitol grounds the capitol police 
classify them as weapons subject to seizure and destruction 
kerrigan said chemical sprays accounted for the vast majority of 
the actual total of the 1270 weapons confiscated at the capitol 
last year a 125 percent increase over 1986 the police said gun 
seizures actually declined to 14 from 28 the previous year 
the balance included knives explosive liquids clubs 
blackjacks and various exotic weapons plus nonlethal stun 
guns which use an electrical jolt to render victims temporarily 
harmless 
asked about kerrigans details russ said he must have 
misinterpreted the figures he received from the capitol police 
senior members of the house panel that heard russ testimony 
discounted suggestions that he might have given misleading figures 
in an attempt to gain support for his security plan 
but rep vic fazio dcalif the subcommittee chairman said 
house members responsible for capitol security intend to take a 
much closer look at the situation in consultation with the senate 
before any decisions are made 
fazio said he has heard conflicting arguments over the need for 
stricter antiterrorist measures we wont be stampeded he 
said 
i dont think jack was trying to mislead us but it does raise 
a question said rep john t myers rind a panel member 
rep jerry lewis of california the subcommitees ranking 
republican agreed with fazios goslow approach 
theyre pushing very hard to increase security everywhere up 
here lewis said we must protect ourselves in this modern age 
of terrorism but i tend to resist any unnecessary steps that would 
hinder the publics access to the capitol 
kerrigan said the sharply higher number of weapons seizures 
probably reflected improved use of metal detectors in the capitol 
building and six nearby office buildings better training of police 
officers and more thorough searches of visitors rather than any 
increase in the number of visitors with criminal intent 
russ said many of the visitors who carry firearms have 
outofstate gun permits but are unaware that the permits are 
invalid on the capitol grounds 
kerrigan said 63 people were prosecuted at the capitol last year 
on illegalweapons charges compared with 50 people in 1986 
