an august 1986 report by the general accounting office the 
investigative arm of congress estimated that 24 percent of all 
federal agency bills were unpaid for more than 30 days 
members of a house government operations subcommittee listened 
sympathetically as other legislators and witnesses for small 
businesses industrial contractors and trade associations urged 
congress to close loopholes in the 1982 prompt payment act which 
requires the federal government to pay its bills within 30 days 
the witnesses endorsed amendments which the senate approved 
unanimously last october that would provide a stricter statutory 
definition of when a federal agency receives an invoice which 
triggers the 30day time clock for payment 
the senate bill also would set a fiveday limit for an agency to 
accept or reject a suppliers goods or services eliminate a 15day 
grace period for payment of late penalties require automatic 
payment of penalties with a double penalty if not paid within 10 
days and prohibit agencies from taking an earlypayment discount 
after payment is due 
raymond s wittig of the us chamber of commerce said the 
governments late payment of bills causes the most damage to small 
businesses which lack large capital funds and depend heavily on 
cash flow to finance their operations 
they often do not have the resources to battle the federal 
bureaucracy over late or incorrect payments wittig said as a 
result small businesses concentrate on selling to customers who 
pay on time 
he added if the government does not pay on time all 
taxpayers and citizens are injured because fewer businesses choose 
to sell to the government this decreased competition raises the 
costs of goods and services purchased by the government 
