in the years first defense spending vote a 
house subcommittee decided wednesday to cut deeply into president 
reagans budget request for his star wars antimissile research 
project according to congressional sources 
the armed services research and development subcommittee also 
increased spending for the midgetman nucleartipped missile and 
sharply reduced the planned budget for deploying mx atomic weapons 
aboard trains said the sources who spoke only on condition of 
anonymity 
the committee met behind closed doors to make the decisions 
the votes by the subcommittee were the first step in the lengthy 
congressional budgeting process the full armed services committee 
will later consider its subcommittee actions before sending the 
pentagon budget bill to the floor of the full house the same 
procedure will also be followed in the senate 
the overall pentagon budget for the 1989 fiscal year will be 
299 billion a figure set by the white house and congress last 
december during negotiations aimed at reducing the federal budget 
deficit 
reagan had sought 45 billion in pentagon spending for star 
wars known formally as the strategic defense initiative 
but the subcommittee approved a 37 billion figure which would 
be an increase of only 3 percent over the current star wars budget 
the sources said 
the fight over the midgetman and the mx involves a pair of 
nucleartipped weapons which have been at the heart of a 
longrunning dispute between the reagan administration and the 
democraticcontrolled congress 
congressional democrats support the single warhead midgetman 
while the air force wants to build more than the 50 of the 
10warhead mx weapons allowed by congress the second 50 mx weapons 
would be based two each aboard 25 trains that would be housed on 
western military bases until a crisis 
reagan had wanted 1 billion for the two programs including 
800 million for study of the railbasing plan while the budget 
contained 200 million for midgetman that latter total was enough 
to keep the program alive until the president who succeeds reagan 
can make a final decision on the dispute according to defense 
secretary frank c carlucci 
as it worked through the budget the subcommittee rejected a 
republicanbacked plan to spend 650 million for mx railroad basing 
plans and another 350 million for midgetman according to the 
sources 
then the panel turned down a democraticproposed plan to spend 
500 million for midgetman and nothing for the mx 
finally the panel agreed to split the 1 billion figure giving 
500 million for research into each weapon 
