the new version effectively exempts companies with less than 50 
workers and farms from having to continue to pay wages and benefits 
for up to a year to workers ordered off the job because of the 
danger continued hazardous exposure would raise for them 
it also puts restrictions on what information from the program 
that workers and former workers could use in pursuing liability 
suits against employers and places a 250 ceiling on the medical 
monitoring expenses that companies would have to pay for each 
covered worker 
do we have a for sale sign on the legislation so that you 
keep watering it down until you get enough votes to pass it 
hatch asked rhetorically calling kennedys action a 
reprehensible tactic 
democrats admitted that kennedys parliamentary maneuver 
although allowed by senate rules could be used to keep repubicans 
from offering amendments of their own but they maintained that was 
not the intent 
democratic leader robert c byrd acknowledged the unfairness 
that has been circumstantially brought about with no malicious 
intent 
because of that byrd said that on thursday he would vote 
against his own motion that was part of a second attempt to bring 
an end to the republican delaying tactics 
metzenbaum attempting to salvage the measure in what appears to 
be a swell of opposition to it said he would urge fellow 
supporters to also vote against putting a limit on the gop delay 
tactics 
a similar bill was passed by the house on a 225186 largely 
partyline vote last october despite vehement opposition from the 
reagan administration 
unions have been seeking the legislation for the past four 
years contending the administration effectively had defanged 
the occupational safety and health administration from protecting 
workers from hazards 
over the past two years metzenbaum had succeeded in winning 
support for the bill from several trade groups and corporations 
including the chemical manufacturers association the american 
electronics association ibm general electric occidental 
petroleum and wr grace and co 
but hundreds of other business groups led by the national 
association of manufacturers and the us chamber of commerce 
remained opposed to the measure in any form 
jerry jasinowki the nams chief economist called the 
legislation a ticking time bomb that could subject employers up 
to billions of dollars in lawsuits each year from workers and 
former workers that the government identifies as being at risk to 
occupational diseases 
the bill would set up a panel of seven scientists in the 
department of health and human services to identify hazards and the 
groups at risk from exposure to them 
the national institute of occupational safety and health would 
then be required to send individual notices to between 100000 and 
300000 individuals every year and employers would be required to 
provide medical monitoring programs for each 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

