<TEXT>
the commerce department said wednesday that 
safeway stores inc has agreed to pay a 995000 penalty to settle 
antiboycott violations in saudi arabia and kuwait last year 
undersecretary paul freedenberg said the sum was the largest 
civil fine in the departments 10year enforcement of federal 
antiboycott laws under the department order safeway has 20 
days to pay the fine 
the antiboycott provisions of the export administration act 
were designed to keep us firms from participation in foreign 
boycotts the us government does not sanction 
the supermarket chain was charged in july 1987 with multiple 
violations in connection with operations of supermarkets in saudi 
arabia and kuwait including refusing to do business with us 
suppliers on a saudi arabia boycott list and using a whitelist 
of approved suppliers from which it offered products for sale to 
arab supermarkets 
safeway was also accused of furnishing prohibited information to 
kuwait about its business relationships with israel and furnishing 
prohibited information about its affiliations with charitable and 
fraternal organizations which support israel 
safeway neither admitted or denied the allegations but agreed to 
pay the civil fine in a settlement march 14 the commerce 
department said 
had the case gone to trial and the supermarket chain found 
guilty on all counts safeway could have received an administrative 
sanction and a civil fine of 45 million the department said 
a safeway spokesman did not immediately return a reporters 
phone calls seeking comment 
