<DOCNO> AP880323-0242 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
church people prefer being led by 
ordained clergy rather than lay professionals even though the 
clergy are not considered very effective a national study of roman 
catholics and protestants finds 
catholics were found somewhat more confident in lay leadership 
than protestants but also favored ordaining women and married men 
which catholicism forbids to keep up the clergy supply 
the yearlong study by hartford seminarys center for social and 
religious research was prompted by growing concern over a clergy 
shortage 
lay leaders at more than 200 parishes across the country were 
asked to consider 12 leadership tasks rating them according to 
importance and how effective the clergy handle them 
for preaching liturgical leadership pastoral counseling 
directing religious education parish evangelization and parish 
planning the gap between importance and effectiveness ranges from 
30 perceent to 40 percent among catholics the study found 
the gap among three protestant denominations surveyed ranged 
between 20 percent and 30 percent the protestants studied were the 
episcopal church the lutheran church in america and the united 
methodist church 
the study also found both protestants and catholics somewhat 
cool toward professional lay leaders but with catholics more 
willing for lay professionals to perform many of the chores now 
undertaken by the clergy 
aproximately 60 percent of members of each denomination 
expressed strong or moderate agreement that the morale in their 
parish or congregation would be adversely affected were they not 
able to secure a fulltime ordained pastor 
also except for lutherans 52 precent over 60 percent of all 
respondents agree that the average lay person responds best to 
ordained leadership the researchers wrote 
when asked what option they would chose if unable to afford a 
fulltime pastor more than 80 percent preferred some form of 
ordained parttime leadership to either fulltime or parttime lay 
leadership 
the seminary an interdenominational theological center 
released a preliminary report on its yearlong study last week a 
fuller report is due later this year 
one purpose was to examine attitudes toward professional lay 
leadership and its comparative costs 
in general protestant clergy were compensated at a rate nearly 
double what catholic priests receive an average of 45005 a year 
for an episcopal priest compared to 26376 a year for a catholic 
priest compensation includes salary plus such items as housing 
health care and retirement benefits 
the study said protestants would save if professional lay 
leaders replaced clergy to run parishes for catholics the costs 
would be closer to the same 
fulltime lay professionals earn an average of 23246 a year 
among united methodists the top among protestants compared to 
16754 among episcoplians and 18527 a year among catholics 
the research team included jackson w carroll hartford 
seminarys research director dean r hoge a sociology professor 
at catholic university in washington dc and the rev francis k 
sheets a church management specialist 
they gathered information from eight metropolitan areas nashua 
nh trenton nj orlando fla mobile ala dallas 
cleveland colorado springs colo and bremerton wash 
the 2209 lay leaders in 201 parishes submitted 1829 completed 
questionaires 
the question of who will minister to churchgoers in the future 
is of critical importance to church officials 
among catholics its estimated that the number of priests will 
decline by 40 percent by the year 2000 the number of catholic 
seminarians declined from 8885 in 1965 to 4063 in 1985 the 
researchers said 
among protestants there is an oversupply of clergy for some 
larger welltodo parishes while theres an increasing shortage 
among smaller parishes unable to afford the cost of fulltime 
clergy members researchers said 
the study found that catholics pay substantially less per 
household to suport their priests compared to protestant 
households catholics contribute an average 28 per household 
annually to pay for priests compared to lutherans who topped the 
survey with an annual contribution of 342 per household 
among other findings 
about 75 percent of catholic lay leaders compared to about half 
the protestants believe most tasks currently done by ordained 
pastors can be done equally well by lay persons with special 
competence for the task 
about half the catholics prefer priests rather than lay people 
give sermons compared to 75 percent among protestants 
more than twothirds of the protestants want their priests to 
lead the confirmation classes compared to 25 percent among 
catholics 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

