<TEXT>
the house showed bipartisan support today for 
a 11 trillion fiscal 1989 budget that averts deep cuts in 
domestic programs and glosses over a failure to comply fully with 
congress deficitreduction agreement with president reagan 
debate began on the plan approved last week by the house budget 
committee with a procedural vote that was adopted without a roll 
call unheardof during the recent years of pitched budget battles 
weve got a miracle said house speaker jim wright dtexas 
expecting easy passage later in the day 
this degree of bipartisanship in developing a budget 
resolution is truly unprecedented said rep delbert l latta of 
ohio senior republican on the budget committee 
the plan would leave a deficit of about 134 billion in the 
spending year beginning oct 1 and would stay within the limits of 
the grammrudman budgetbalancing law the deficit would be about 
5 billion higher than with reagans budget mostly because the 
president proposed to sell off more government assets 
the lawmakers electionyear plan would freeze or slightly trim 
most domestic agencies it would spend 15 billion on aids 
research a little more than reagan proposed but not boost the 
space program as much as the president asked it rejects his plans 
to cancel aid to mass transit and other popular domestic subsidies 
as in the presidents plan the governments total cash outlays 
on the military foreign aid and certain domestic programs would be 
held to levels set last fall when the president and congressional 
leaders held a budget summit 
however that agreement also contained limits for budget 
authority the legal obligations by agencies for spending that 
could stretch over more than one fiscal year the house plan would 
violate the agreement if it werent for some accounting wizardry 
to avoid breaking the limit on budget authority the house 
budget committee shifted about 4 billion in the domestic budget 
mostly ongoing agriculture credit expenses outside of the 
categories controlled by the summit pact 
the accounting change made room for the kind of budget lawmakers 
support one that would not terminate urban and rural development 
programs and other items the president sought to end 
in its report to the house the budget committee said the 
technical changes were the only way it could find to hit the budget 
marks for both outlays and budget authority 
it is not our intention that this budget authority 
adjustment not result in higher outlays in fy 1989 than the 1692 
billion domestic allowed under the summit cap the 
committee said 
rep william h gray iii dpa chairman of the committee said 
he believed it stayed within the budget pact the outlay is what 
youre really going to be judged by he said 
despite the committee language the budget technique could lead 
to higher spending allowances when the fiscal blueprint is 
translated later into actual spending bills the presidents office 
of management and budget send a letter to congress critical of the 
approach and promising to monitor spending closely as the budget is 
implemented 
house action on the budget today was the earliest in years as 
democratic leaders were keeping to their vow to put fiscal affairs 
on schedule this year 
members of the senate budget committee have begun private 
meetings on their version the two chambers must agree on identical 
budgets by april 15 to meet their deadline 
the budget resolution is a guideline for congress fiscal 
legislation and it does not require the presidents signature 
with the accounting changes the house budget would hit exactly 
the limits in the budget summit pact those are 2995 billion in 
budget authority and 2940 billion in outlays for the military 
1481 billion in budget authority and 1692 billion in outlays 
for annuallyappropriated domestic programs and 181 billion in 
budget authority and 161 billion in outlays on foreign aid 
the summit agreement also included 14 billion in new taxes for 
fiscal 1989 those levies were enacted last december and congress 
plans no further increases this year 
the grammrudman law mandates a deficit of 136 billion in 
fiscal 1989 as an interim step toward a balanced budget by fiscal 
1993 neither the house plan nor reagans met that mark without 
relying on selling government assets which arent counted under 
grammrudman 
however both plans would be within 10 billion of the goal 
keeping below the threshold at which the law would mandate 
automatic acrosstheboard spending cuts 
those estimates are based on the white house assumptions for 
economic growth and government performance next year estimates by 
the nonpartisan congressional budget office which are less 
optimistic show the deficit some 35 billion higher 
