<TEXT>
texaco inc on wednesday won final 
bankruptcy court approval for a plan that would settle its 
multibilliondollar dispute with pennzoil co and bring it out of 
chapter 11 protection early next month 
after a day and a half of closing arguments us bankruptcy 
court judge howard schwartzberg confirmed the reorganization plan 
which features an agreement by texaco to pay pennzoil co 3 
billion to drop a 103 billion judgement held by pennzoil against 
the nations thirdlargest oil company 
when the plan goes into effect on april 7 texaco will deliver 
the money to pennzoil and will be officially free from the legal 
constraints that have limited its operations since the company 
filed for protection from its creditors last april 12 
it was the largest corporate bankruptcy in us history 
texaco said it was driven to take that action to avoid having to 
pay a potentially ruinous 11 billion security bond while appealing 
the judgment held by pennzoil 
a houston jury awarded the judgment to houstonbased pennzoil in 
november 1985 after finding that texaco had improperly interfered 
with a pennzoil acquisition of part of getty oil company so texaco 
could buy getty itself 
schwartzbergs approval marked the last step required for texaco 
to emerge from bankruptcy protection under federal law 
texaco officials and pennzoil chairman j hugh liedtke expressed 
profound relief that the fouryear ordeal of litigation that had 
paralyzed both companies was finally over 
i must say it has not been a particularly pleasant experience 
but it had to be done said j hugh liedtke pennzoils 
chairman 
liedtke said he never doubted that the jurys verdict would be 
vindicated despite lingering criticism from some quarters 
quite frankly all the smoke aside people dont pay 3 
billion for something who dont have some liability he said 
told of that remark texaco chairman alfred c decrane who at 
tuesdays hearing had stoutly defended texacos view that it had 
done nothing wrong said what we did here today is to settle 
this matter 
noting that texacos only other choice was a highly risky 
allornothing attempt to win a us supreme court reversal he 
said the company settled to end that litigation 
in announcing his decision to confirm the plan schwartzberg 
noted that 96 percent of texacos shares were voted in favor of the 
package which was laboriously worked out among pennzoil texaco 
and committees representing texacos creditors and shareholders 
he also noted that the plan provides for full payment to 
texacos creditors with interest and had been supported by 
representatives of all the principal parties during the final 
confirmation hearings 
the only lingering bone of contention was the presence of 
provisions in the plan granting immunity to all parties involved in 
the original texacogettypennzoil matter 
on tuesday dissident shareholders reluctantly dropped 16 suits 
against texaco saying they would support the plan knowing that 
the company would be in far worse condition if it were not approved 
the dissidents contended along with texacos largest 
shareholder takeover artist carl c icahn that the releases gave 
away a chance for texaco to recoup some of its losses by suing the 
parties responsible for texacos ultimate defeat in houston 
icahn who owns 148 percent of texacos stock also protested 
that the measures served to entrench management and diminish its 
accountability to shareholders 
while he voted in favor of the plan he urged the court to 
strike the releases from the plan 
schwartzberg refused to do so agreeing with arguments by both 
pennzoil and texaco that the releases were on balance in the 
best interest of texaco 
noting that pennzoil not texaco had inserted the provisions 
schwartzberg said it appeared inevitable that endless litigation 
would continue without the releases which all parties wanted to 
avoid 
he also suggested it was questionable that texaco officials 
could be found guilty of fiduciary irresponsibility for their roles 
in the getty affair 
liedtke said the judges action would trigger plans already set 
up to borrow a very substantial part of the 3 billion from a 
consortium of banks which it will begin investing in shortterm 
notes 
when it receives the payment from texaco it will then repay the 
banks liedtke said 
asked if pennzoil would be interested in buying any texaco 
assets liedtke said it could not be done without their 
permission because of a mutual agreement forestalling such 
action for five years 
he said the company would be studying longerrange plans for the 
money adding that decisions could not be expected for at least 
several weeks 
with the case virtually closed liedtke said he planned to sit 
and think a little bit and that he hoped to retire from his 
chief executive post when the company holds its annual meeting next 
month 
</TEXT>
