<TEXT>
in a case with implications for all north 
american automakers a canadian trade panel wednesday ruled that 
lowprice imports from hyundai motor co of south korea had not 
injured domestic manufacturers 
the tribunal found no evidence of material injury to the 
canadian subsidiaries of ford motor co and and general motors 
corp which had accused hyundai of dumping its hatchbacks and 
small sedans at belowcost prices to gain a foothold in the north 
american market 
revenue canada a department of the federal government 
initially agreed with ford and gm and imposed preliminary duties of 
26 percent on hyundai imports 
but the key to the case was not whether hyundai was selling cars 
in canada at prices below those on the south korean domestic 
market ford and gm also had to prove they suffered material 
injury and failed to do so according to the threemember 
canadian import tribunal 
the government panel found no evidence of damage and ordered the 
preliminary duties imposed last november refunded it was the first 
case involving autos ever handled by the trade tribunal officials 
said 
all proceedings against hyundai motor co with regard to 
dumping will be terminated tribunal secretary art trudeau said 
in ottawa where the decision was announced 
hyundai spokesman greg young said the refund amounted to 
millions and millions of dollars posted in bonds 
the feeling here today is like a cloud has been removed from 
over our head said young 
george peapples president and general manager of general motors 
of canada expressed disbelief at the finding 
it has been and it remains our contention that continued 
unrestrained dumping by hyundai will result in lost jobs and 
investment in the canadian automotive industry peapples said in 
a statement 
given the deputy minister of revenues findings of dumping 
margins in excess of 26 percent its difficult to comprehend that 
the tribunal did not find any injury whatsoever 
gm spokesman nick hall said he could not comment on whether a 
judicial appeal will be made until the tribunal explains the 
reasons for its verdict next month theres been a lot of time 
and effort spent on it already hall said 
ford of canada spokesman jim hartford said the ruling points to 
flaws in canadian trade law and dangers lurking in the 
comprehensive canadaus free trade agreement scheduled for 
ratification this year 
he said ford was unable to prove substantial injury from hyundai 
imports because canadian law looked solely at ford production and 
sales in canada where smallcar production has been phased out 
instead of examining fords integrated north american operations 
the tribunal was severely handicapped by the narrow scope of 
trade law coverage in canada hartford said were alarmed by 
the implications todays decision has for other industries which 
may become rationalized under the freetrade agreement 
the canadian auto industry responsible for 140000 direct jobs 
is integrally linked with us operations under a dutyfree 1965 
auto pact between the two countries treating the continent as a 
single market 
the canadian government made a crucial intervention on hyundais 
behalf in the antidumping hearing that ended march 10 the bureau 
of competition policy said hyundai had fostered competition in the 
smallcar market and kept car prices down 
hyundai came to canada in 1984 and within a year had a 21 
percent share of the subcompact market with sales of 79072 ponies 
and stellars the cheapest of its hatchbacks sold for 6000 
canadian or 4500 in american dollars 
hyundai then entered the us market where it grabbed a 26 
percent share last year with sales of 264000 excels 
when ford and gm accused hyundai of dumping and the government 
initially concurred hyundais sales plummeted and some dealers 
resigned the company expects to sell about 45000 cars in canada 
this year third behind honda and toyota in the smallcar market 
auto industry analysts said victory for ford and gm would have 
opened a pandoras box in which us carmakers might have launched 
similar attacks on japanese importers as well as hyundai 
operations south of the border 
i can only assume other importers will evaluate the case today 
very closely and apply it to their operations said young 
</TEXT>
